Claim 2: Uniqueness up to isomorphism. For each n>1, we see p(x)=x^{p^{n}}-x is separable since p'(x)=-1\neq 0. Then p(x) has p^{n} roots in the splitting field \Bbbk . Let S\subseteq \Bbbk  be the set of roots of p(x). For \alpha ,\beta \in  S we have
\begin {align*} p(\alpha +\beta )&=(\alpha +\beta )^{p^{n}}-(\alpha +\beta )\\ &=\alpha ^{p^{n}}-\alpha +\beta ^{p^{n}}-\beta \\ &=p(\alpha )+p(\beta )=0\end {align*}
so S is closed under addition, and also
\begin {align*} p(\alpha \beta )&=(\alpha \beta )^{p^{n}}-(\alpha \beta )\\ &=\alpha ^{p^{n}}\beta ^{p^{n}}-\alpha \beta \\ &=\alpha \beta -\alpha \beta =0\end {align*}
so S is closed under multiplication. It then follows that S is a subfield of \Bbbk . But \Bbbk  is the smallest field extension of \mathbb {F} containing S, so S=\Bbbk . Then \Bbbk  has p^{n} elements, therefore has degree n over \mathbb {F}.

